Hvsp 0.0.0.9000
  • Reference

    Hierarchical Vintage Sparse PCA (Hvsp)

    Hvsp.Rd

    The hierarchical vintage sparse PCA (Hvsp) that combines vintage sparse PCA by Rohe and Zeng (2022) and hierarchical community detection (HCD) by Li et al. (2020).

    Usage

    Hvsp(A, stopping = "NB", n.min = 25, D = NULL, notree = TRUE, ...)

    Arguments

    A

    input adjacency matrix. Can be standard R matrix or dsCMatrix (or other type in package Matrix)

    stopping

    stopping rule. "NB" (default) -- non-backtracking matrix spectrum, "ECV" -- edge cross-validation, "Fix"-- fixed D layers of partitioning ECV is nonparametric rank evaluation by cross-validation -- a more generally applicable approach without assuming SBM or its variants. Also available for weighted networks. It is believed to be more robust than NB but less effective if the true model is close to BTSBM. ECV is computationally much more intensive.

    n.min

    the algorithm will stop splitting if the current size is <= 2*n.min.

    D

    the number of layers to partition, if stopping=="Fix".

    notree

    if TRUE, will not produce the data.tree object or the community similarity matrix. Only the cluster label and the tree path strings will be returned. This typically makes the runing faster.

    ...

    optional arguments for vsp()

    Value

    Output a HCD object

    results
    labels

    clustering label

    ncl

    number of clusters

    cluster.tree

    cluster tree from data.tree

    P

    estimated probability matrix

    node.bin.sim.mat

    nodes' similarity matrix

    comm.bin.sim.mat

    clusters' similarity matrix

    tree.path

    nodes' tree path

    cent

    centrality/importance score for vsp

    Examples

    tt <- BTSBM(1024, 2, c(1, .3, .09), 50)
A <- tt$A.list[[1]]
Hvsp(A)
